{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17584374","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17584374"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:44:31+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:44:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14455"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14455","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14455"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.29,0.49,0.16,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7150"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114018"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7150","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7150"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14455"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96033"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"40"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4903"},{"type":"tags","id":"4914"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17068"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17136"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114018","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114018"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following correctly describes turbulent blood flow?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Fluid moves in parallel layers","Velocity is highest at the vessel wall","There is loss of energy due to increased friction","A decrease in pressure is needed to maintain flow","It is the predominant type of blood flow in the body"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn turbulent blood flow, fluid particles move in a chaotic and non-parallel manner, which leads to increased friction and energy loss as heat. Turbulent flow occurs under conditions of high velocity, large vessel diameter, or low blood viscosity and can lead to increased resistance within the vessel. The correct option is that \u003Cstrong\u003Ethere is loss of energy due to increased friction\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFluid moves in parallel layers\u003C/strong\u003E describes laminar flow, not turbulent flow. \u003Cstrong\u003EVelocity is highest at the vessel wall\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect; in both laminar and turbulent flow, velocity is highest at the centre of the vessel and lowest at the vessel wall due to friction. \u003Cstrong\u003EA decrease in pressure is needed to maintain flow\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect; turbulent flow actually requires a higher pressure gradient to maintain the same flow rate compared to laminar flow. \u003Cstrong\u003EIt is the predominant type of blood flow in the body\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect; laminar flow is the main type of blood flow under normal physiological conditions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETurbulent flow typically occurs in large vessels, at branch points, or in pathological conditions such as atherosclerosis or valvular heart disease. It is less efficient than laminar flow due to the energy loss from friction and can often be heard as a bruit or murmur.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Turbulent blood flow is characterized by irregular fluid movements, energy loss due to friction, and audible flow.","Laminar flow is the predominant type of blood flow in the body under normal conditions."],"references":["Tucker WD, Arora Y, Mahajan K. Anatomy, Blood Vessels. [Updated 2023 Aug 8]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK470401/","Hemmings, H. C., \u0026 Egan, T. D. Pharmacology and physiology for anesthesia e-book: foundations and clinical application. 2012. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Tortora, G. J., Derrickson, B., Burkett, B., Cooke, J., Di Pietro, F., Diversi, T., ... \u0026 Summers, S.. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 3rd Asia-Pacific Edition. 2022. John Wiley \u0026 Sons"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96033"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14455"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96033","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96033"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-14T19:25:43+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-14T19:25:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7150"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114018"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"40","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/40"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\u2699\ufe0f","name":"Physiology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"4"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"ty